  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Most developed countries have comprehensive AML laws\n\n2. Financial institutions are required to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n3. International standards are set by organizations like:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n\n4. Regulations typically cover:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Securities firms\n- Insurance companies\n- Money transfer services\n\n5. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Large financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThe United States, European Union, United Kingdom, and many other countries have robust AML regulatory frameworks that continue to evolve to address emerging financial technologies and criminal methods.",
